Can you reconstruct the code snippets to make a 
working Java program that produces the output 
listed below? NOTE: To do this exercise, you need 
one NEW piece of info—if you look in the API for 
ArrayList, you’11 find a second add method that takes 
two arguments:
add(int index, Object 0)
It lets you specify to the 
ArrayList where to put the object you’re adding.
Exercise
Code Magnets
if (a.contains(“three”)) {
 a.add(“four”);
}
import java.util.*;
public class ArrayListMagnet {
ArrayList<String> a = new ArrayList<String>();
 public static void main (String[] args) {
a.add(0,”zero”);
a.add(1,”one”);
 a.add(2,”two”);
a.add(3,”three”);
printAL(a);
a.remove(2);
if (a.indexOf(“four”) != 4) {
 a.add(4, “4.2”);
}
if (a.contains(“two”)) {
 a.add(“2.2”);
}
 public static void printAL(ArrayList<String> al) {
for (String element : al) {
System.out.print(element + “ “);
}
System.out.println(“ “);
}
}
}
printAL(a);
printAL(a);
printAL(a);
